// Java code for a button
import javax.swing.*;

public class ButtonExample {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    JButton button = new JButton("Click me!");
    button.addActionListener(e -> System.out.println("Button clicked!"));
    JFrame frame = new JFrame("Button Example");
    frame.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
    frame.getContentPane().add(button, BorderLayout.CENTER);
    frame.pack();
    frame.setVisible(true);
  }
}
```
This code creates a button with the text "Click me!" and adds an action listener to it that prints "Button clicked!" to the console when the button is clicked. The `JFrame` object is used to create a window that contains the button, and the `BorderLayout` class is used to specify where the button should be placed in the window. The `pack()` method is called on the frame to size it appropriately based on its contents, and the `setVisible(true)` method is called to make the window visible.
